In article &lt;opal-2302971655570 ... @desm-09-28.dialup.netins.net&gt;,
o ... @netins.net wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Can anyone tell me how to find info on cleaning cast iron kitchen items?
&gt;Thank you!

"/> Are you planning to *use* the item, or just display it?

If you are planning to use one, do *not* use any soap or cleanser on it. This will completely ruin any seasoning previous owners have done to the item. Either try to &quot;bake&quot; the stuff off at very high heat or use steel wool and warm water and lots of elbow grease. Be sure to dry the pot thoroughly so that new rust doesn't form and give it a light coat of vegetable oil spray.

If you already stripped off the seasoning, you'll have to start all over again. Coat the pan liberally with oil and put it in a hot oven for about an hour. Let it cool, then wipe the oil off. Coat the pan inside and out, and if it has a lid, do the lid as well. *Never* use soap on the seasoned pan. Usually, you can just wipe it out when you're done cooking; if something must be removed just scrub it out under warm plain water.

I have several iron pans that have been in my family for a long time, and I wouldn't trade an iron pan for the most expensive no-sticks in the world. But could someone please tell me why my big Griswold with the &quot;large&quot; symbol on the bottom is so collectable? It doesn't cook any better than the Lodge's I've gotten from the Service Merchandise...

-- Courtney

