"/> I don't agree.

First off, if you have just purchased the piece, chances are you don't
know where it has been and what it has been used for. My stepmother
uses hers to slop the pigs!

Second, many times the gook is so thick that it won't scrub off evenly
and you will end up with the iron burnished in some spots instead of
the original and desirable black tone. This devalues the piece.

Finally, many of the older folks that I have talked with report that
they cleansed and reseasoned their iron on a yearly basis.

If you have the old family iron, then, at least, you know where it's
been and the grease has a pedigree that you can trust.

To answer your question about Griswold and why it is collectable, it's
old and is some of the finest iron cookware casting of the twentieth
century. Look at the smooth interior of your skillet and compare it to
the unpolished surface on your new Lodge skillets. There is a great
difference. It is possible that you have a carbon build up that
obscures this. I have had Griswold skillets of the large logo variety
that were nearly mirror finsh on the inside.

To sum up, when cleaned and seasoned correctly, both cooking properties
and collector's value of the piece are improved and it in no way
damages the iron.

Enjoy your skillets
Glenn

